\section{Files}{

Each term lives in \verb{inst/terms/<term>.<directed|undirected>.yml}, where
\verb{<term>} is the canonical \code{ergm} term name as written in a model formula
(e.g., \code{gwesp}, \code{b1nodematch}). Terms available for both directed and
undirected networks get one file per variant; bipartite terms use
\code{undirected}. Each file has two top-level entries: \code{plot} (the network
drawing specification) and \code{math} (a LaTeX expression). No parser changes
are needed for new terms: files are looked up by term name.
}

\section{Math notation}{

\itemize{
\item \eqn{y_{ij}}: tie indicator. Undirected statistics sum over
\eqn{i<j}; directed statistics sum over \eqn{i \neq j}.
\item \eqn{x_i}: vertex attribute value of node \eqn{i};
\eqn{x_{ij}}: dyadic covariate value (e.g., \code{edgecov}).
\item \eqn{\mathbf{1}(\cdot)}: indicator function (\verb{\\mathbf\{1\}} in
LaTeX).
\item Attribute levels: \eqn{k} for a single level (factor terms),
\eqn{(k, l)} for mixing pairs, and \eqn{(p, q)} for center/leaf
values in star-mixing terms.
\item Bipartite modes: \eqn{B_1} (first mode) and \eqn{B_2} (second
mode); \eqn{n_{B_1}} and \eqn{n_{B_2}} for the mode sizes.
\item Geometrically weighted terms follow the Hunter (2007)
parameterization, e.g.
\eqn{\exp(\tau) \sum_i [1 - (1 - e^{-\tau})^i] EP_i(y)}, where the
exponent is the summation index and \eqn{EP_i}, \eqn{DP_i}, and
\eqn{D_i} are the edgewise shared partner, dyadwise shared partner,
and degree counts.
}
Always verify a new formula against the \code{ergm} term manual (see
\link[ergm:ergmTerm]{ergm::ergmTerm} and \code{\link[ergm:search.ergmTerms]{ergm::search.ergmTerms()}}) and the source
literature. When the manual is ambiguous, compare the formula
numerically against \code{summary(nw ~ term)} on a small test network.
}

\section{Drawing conventions}{

The \code{plot} entry supports \code{edgelist}, \code{vcolor}, \code{vshape}, \code{vsize},
\code{ecolor}, \code{elinetype}, and \code{layout} (with \code{x} and \code{y} coordinates).
Edgelists are chains like \code{"0->1->2, 0->3"}: each consecutive pair is
one edge. Per-vertex vectors follow the node order obtained from the
parsed edgelist (unique node ids, all tail nodes first, then head
nodes); render the figure to double-check the mapping.
\itemize{
\item \strong{Vertex color}: \code{black} marks the focal structure of a
term; \code{gray} marks non-focal context, both attribute-irrelevant
nodes and structurally non-focal nodes (e.g., the shared partners
in \code{gwesp}/\code{gwdsp}); \code{orange} marks nodes whose attribute enters
the statistic (matched pairs share orange); mixing terms use
\code{orange} vs. teal (\code{"#008080"}, quoted in the YAML) for the two
attribute categories, a colorblind-friendly pairing. These colors
drive the explanatory notes appended below rendered tables, so
use them consistently.
\item \strong{Vertex shape}: \code{square} marks first-mode (\eqn{B_1})
nodes and \code{circle} marks second-mode (\eqn{B_2}) nodes in bipartite
drawings. One-mode drawings use circles only.
\item \strong{Layout}: bipartite drawings place the first mode on the
left and the second mode on the right.
\item \strong{Vertex size}: \code{1.0} for focal or attribute-relevant
nodes, \code{.5} for context nodes.
\item \strong{Edges}: solid black for focal ties; \code{gray} for
context ties (e.g., the two-paths in shared-partner terms);
dashed (\code{elinetype: 2}) for match/covariate annotations;
\code{orange} when the edge itself carries the covariate
(e.g., \code{edgecov}).
\item Directedness comes from the file name; arrows are drawn
automatically for \code{.directed.yml} terms.
}
